        <h2>Special Characters Examples</h2>
        <p>Here are some special characters and their HTML entity representations:</p>
        
        <ul>
            <li>&amp; - Represents the ampersand character: &amp;</li>
            <li>&lt; - Represents the less-than sign: &lt;</li>
            <li>&gt; - Represents the greater-than sign: &gt;</li>
            <li>&copy; - Represents the copyright symbol: &copy;</li>
            <li>&reg; - Represents the registered trademark symbol: &reg;</li>
            <li>&trade; - Represents the trademark symbol: &trade;</li>
        </ul>
        
        
        <h2>Example Usage</h2>
        <p>&copy; 2024 Your Company. All rights reserved.</p>
        <p>This product is certified &reg; for quality.</p>
        <p>Our brand is recognized worldwide as a symbol of quality &trade;.</p>
        
        
        <h2>HTML Structure Explanation</h2>
        <p>HTML documents are structured with elements enclosed in tags:</p>
        
        <ul>
            <li>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; - Specifies the document type and HTML version.</li>
            <li>&lt;html&gt; - Root element that wraps all content.</li>
            <li>&lt;head&gt; - Contains metadata and links to external resources.</li>
            <li>&lt;meta&gt; - Provides metadata about the HTML document (e.g., character set).</li>
            <li>&lt;title&gt; - Sets the title of the document displayed in the browser tab.</li>
            <li>&lt;body&gt; - Contains the visible content of the document.</li>
            <li>&lt;h1&gt; to &lt;h6&gt; - Heading elements used to define headings.</li>
            <li>&lt;p&gt; - Paragraph element used for text content.</li>
            <li>&lt;ul&gt; and &lt;li&gt; - Used for unordered lists and list items.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <p>These elements form the structure of an HTML document, defining how content is organized and displayed in a web browser.</p>
